{"title_page": "Branscombe Richmond", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Branscombe Richmond\n| image       = Branscombe Richmond Portrait.jpg\n| caption     = Richmond at the Halloween in [[Lahaina]] festivities in October 2011\n| birth_name  = Branscombe Leo Charles Richmond\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1955|8|8|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Character actor\n| years_active = 1974&ndash;present\n| spouse      = Lei Richmond\n}}\n\n'''Branscombe Richmond''' (born August 8, 1955),<ref>According to the State of California. ''California Birth Index, 1905-1995''. Center for Health Statistics, California Department of Health Services, Sacramento, California. At Ancestry.com</ref> sometimes credited in films as '''Richmond Branscombe''', '''Ranscombe Richmon''', '''Ranhome Quickman''' or '''Branscom Richmond''', is an [[United States|American]] [[character actor]] and stuntman of English, Native American, Native Hawaiian, French, French Polynesian, Spanish and Portuguese descent.\n\n==Life and career==\nRichmond was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], the son of Leo C. Richmond, an actor and stuntman.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/75/Branscombe-Richmond.html Branscombe Richmond Biography (1955-)]</ref>\n\nHe appeared as a policeman named Harker in the pilot and all 10 episodes of ''[[Hawaiian Heat]]'' in the fall of 1984 on ABC. The show quickly failed pitted against the ratings juggernaut ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''. In the fall of 1986, he then appeared as another cop, Sergeant Luke Halui, in all 13 episodes of ''[[Heart of the City (TV series)|Heart of the City]]''. It was the second lowest rated show that season, due to having to do battle with NBC's Top 20 hits ''[[The Golden Girls]]'' and ''[[Amen (TV series)|Amen]]'', as well as losing out to CBS's show ''[[The New Mike Hammer]]''. It ranked only 78th out of 79 shows and lasted only 13 episodes.\n\nProbably his most well known and prominent television role was in 1990s hit syndicated television series ''[[Renegade (TV series)|Renegade]]'' as Bobby Sixkiller. He also appeared in a minor role as Moki in the pilot episode of ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'', before the role was taken over by another actor for the series (he played several bad guy bit parts in later episodes). His many other television appearances include series such as ''[[Walker, Texas Ranger]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'' and ''[[The Highwayman (TV series)|The Highwayman]]''. He has appeared in ''[[Star Trek III: The Search for Spock]]'', ''[[Action Jackson (1988 film)|Action Jackson]]'', ''[[Journey 2: The Mysterious Island]]'', ''[[Aces: Iron Eagle III]]'', ''[[Harley Davidson and the Marlboro Man]]'', ''[[Christopher Columbus: The Discovery]]'', and in ''[[The Scorpion King]]'', as Mathayus's half-brother.\n\nHe was inducted to the [[Motorcycle Hall of Fame]] in 2003.<ref>{{mhof|356}}</ref> Grindcore band [[Anal Cunt]]  paid tribute to him in a track called \"Branscombe Richmond\" on their album ''[[I Like It When You Die]]''.\n\nHe now has taken part in being a voice actor for the hit game \"Apex Legends\", voicing the character Gibraltar.\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[Two-Minute Warning]]'' (1976) as Bystander with Blood on His Hands (uncredited)\n* ''[[Rollercoaster (1977 film)|Rollercoaster]]'' (1977) as Minor Role (uncredited)\n* ''[[MacArthur (film)|MacArthur]]'' (1977) as Korean Soldier (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Kentucky Fried Movie]]'' (1977) as Guard (segment \"A Fistful of Yen\")\n* ''[[The Chicken Chronicles]]'' (1977) as Mark\n* ''Kill the Golden Goose'' (1979) as Mahuna\n* ''[[The Fish That Saved Pittsburgh]]'' (1979) as Winston Running Hawk\n* ''[[Magnum P.I.]]'' (1982) as native killed by curse\n* ''[[Killpoint]]'' (1984) as Informant in Locker Room (uncredited)\n* ''[[Star Trek III: The Search for Spock]]'' (1984) as Klingon Gunner #2\n* ''[[Cannonball Run II]]'' (1984) as Biker (uncredited)\n* ''[[Hawaiian Heat]]'' (1984) as Harker (main role)\n* ''[[Commando (1985 film)|Commando]]'' (1985) as Vega\n* ''[[Never Too Young to Die]]'' (1986) as Minkie's Partner \n* ''[[MacGyver]]'' (1986, TV Series) as Grade\n* ''[[Firewalker (film)|Firewalker]]'' (1986) as Mexican Bar Fight Person (uncredited)\n* ''[[Heart of the City (TV series)|Heart of the City]]'' (1986\u20131987, TV Series) as Sergeant Luke Halui (main role)\n* ''No Safe Haven'' (1987) as Manuel\n* ''[[Best Seller]]'' (1987) as Longshoreman #1\n* ''[[The Hidden (film)|The Hidden]]'' (1987) as Roberts\n* ''[[Action Jackson (1988 film)|Action Jackson]]'' (1988) as Poolroom Thug #2\n* ''[[The New Adventures of Pippi Longstocking]]'' (1988) as Fridolf\n* ''[[Hero and the Terror]]'' (1988) as Victor\n* ''[[Licence to Kill]]'' (1989) as Barrelhead Bar Patron (uncredited)\n* ''[[L.A. Bounty]]'' (1989) as Willis\n* ''[[Cage (film)|Cage]]'' (1989) as Diablo\n* ''[[Hard to Kill]]'' (1990) as Max Quentero\n* ''[[El Diablo (1990 film)|El Diablo]]'' (1990) as Dancing Bear\n* ''[[Joe Versus the Volcano]]'' (1990) as Waponi (uncredited)\n* ''[[Kindergarten Cop]]'' (1990) as Club Bouncer\n* ''[[The Perfect Weapon (1991 film)|The Perfect Weapon]]'' (1991) as Bartender\n* ''[[Trabbi Goes to Hollywood]]'' (1991) as Bouncer\n* ''[[Showdown in Little Tokyo]]'' (1991) as Man in Door (uncredited)\n* ''Harley Davidson and the Marlboro Man'' (1991) as Big Indian\n* ''[[The Taking of Beverly Hills]]'' (1991) as Benitez\n* ''[[Curly Sue]]'' (1991) as Albert\n* ''[[Grand Canyon (1991 film)|Grand Canyon]]'' (1991) as Ace Cop\n* ''[[Aces: Iron Eagle III]]'' (1992) as Rapist\n* ''[[Article 99]]'' (1992) as Green Beret Waiting in Line (uncredited)\n* ''[[Batman Returns]]'' (1992) as Terrifying Clown #1\n* ''[[Christopher Columbus: The Discovery]]'' (1992) as Indian Chieftain\n* ''Inside Edge'' (1992) as Henderson\n* ''[[Nemesis (1992 film)|Nemesis]]'' (1992) as Mexican Man\n* ''Sweet Justice'' (1992) as Biker\n* ''[[Renegade (TV series)|Renegade]]'' (1992\u20131997, TV Series) as Bobby Sixkiller (main role)\n* ''[[Sunset Grill (film)|Sunset Grill]]'' (1993) as Gang Member #1\n* ''[[DaVinci's War]]'' (1993) as Don Ho\n* ''[[CIA II: Target Alexa]]'' (1993) as General Mendosa\n* ''No Escape No Return'' (1993) as Rapist (uncredited)\n* ''Hard Vice'' (1994) as Tony\n* ''[[The Corpse Had a Familiar Face]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[To the Limit (1995 film)|To the Limit]]'' (1995) as Don Williams\n* ''[[The Scorpion King]]'' (2002) as Jesup\n* ''[[Black Cloud (film)|Black Cloud]]'' (2004) as Peter\n* ''Angels with Angles'' (2005) as El Capitan\n* ''[[Forgetting Sarah Marshall]]'' (2008) as Keoki (small cameo)\n* ''Taken by Force'' (2010) as Dakota\n* ''[[Just Go with It]]'' (2011) as Bartender\n* ''[[Soul Surfer (film)|Soul Surfer]]'' (2011) as Ben Aipa\n* ''Born to Ride'' (2011) as Dean\n* ''[[Journey 2: The Mysterious Island]]'' (2012) as Tour Guide\n* ''[[Mike and Dave Need Wedding Dates]]'' (2016) as Kalani - BBQ Chef\n* ''Angel by Thursday'' (2016) as Rosales\n* ''Kuleana'' (2017) as The Moke\n* ''[[Chicago Med]]'' (2019) as Keoni\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|725079}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richmond, Branscombe}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American people who self-identify as being of Native American descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French Polynesian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Native Hawaiian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Branscombe Richmond\n| image       = Branscombe Richmond Portrait.jpg\n| caption     = Richmond at the Halloween in [[Lahaina]] festivities in October 2011\n| birth_name  = Branscombe Leo Charles Richmond\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1955|8|8|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Character actor\n| years_active = 1974&ndash;present\n| spouse      = Lei Richmond\n}}\n\n'''Branscombe Richmond''' (born August 8, 1955),<ref>According to the State of California. ''California Birth Index, 1905-1995''. Center for Health Statistics, California Department of Health Services, Sacramento, California. At Ancestry.com</ref> sometimes credited in films as '''Richmond Branscombe''', '''Ranscombe Richmon''', '''Ranhome Quickman''' or '''Branscom Richmond''', is an [[United States|American]] [[character actor]] and stuntman of English, Native American, Native Hawaiian, French, French Polynesian, Spanish and Portuguese descent.\n\n==Life and career==\nRichmond was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], the son of Leo C. Richmond, an actor and stuntman.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/75/Branscombe-Richmond.html Branscombe Richmond Biography (1955-)]</ref>\n\nHe appeared as a policeman named Harker in the pilot and all 10 episodes of ''[[Hawaiian Heat]]'' in the fall of 1984 on ABC. The show quickly failed pitted against the ratings juggernaut ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''. In the fall of 1986, he then appeared as another cop, Sergeant Luke Halui, in all 13 episodes of ''[[Heart of the City (TV series)|Heart of the City]]''. It was the second lowest rated show that season, due to having to do battle with NBC's Top 20 hits ''[[The Golden Girls]]'' and ''[[Amen (TV series)|Amen]]'', as well as losing out to CBS's show ''[[The New Mike Hammer]]''. It ranked only 78th out of 79 shows and lasted only 13 episodes.\n\nProbably his most well known and prominent television role was in 1990s hit syndicated television series ''[[Renegade (TV series)|Renegade]]'' as Bobby Sixkiller. He also appeared in a minor role as Moki in the pilot episode of ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'', before the role was taken over by another actor for the series (he played several bad guy bit parts in later episodes). His many other television appearances include series such as ''[[Walker, Texas Ranger]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'' and ''[[The Highwayman (TV series)|The Highwayman]]''. He has appeared in ''[[Star Trek III: The Search for Spock]]'', ''[[Action Jackson (1988 film)|Action Jackson]]'', ''[[Journey 2: The Mysterious Island]]'', ''[[Aces: Iron Eagle III]]'', ''[[Harley Davidson and the Marlboro Man]]'', ''[[Christopher Columbus: The Discovery]]'', and in ''[[The Scorpion King]]'', as Mathayus's half-brother.\n\nHe was inducted to the [[Motorcycle Hall of Fame]] in 2003.<ref>{{mhof|356}}</ref> Grindcore band [[Anal Cunt]]  paid tribute to him in a track called \"Branscombe Richmond\" on their album ''[[I Like It When You Die]]''.\n\nHe now has taken part in being a voice actor for the hit game \"Apex Legends\", voicing the character Gibraltar.\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[Two-Minute Warning]]'' (1976) as Bystander with Blood on His Hands (uncredited)\n* ''[[Rollercoaster (1977 film)|Rollercoaster]]'' (1977) as Minor Role (uncredited)\n* ''[[MacArthur (film)|MacArthur]]'' (1977) as Korean Soldier (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Kentucky Fried Movie]]'' (1977) as Guard (segment \"A Fistful of Yen\")\n* ''[[The Chicken Chronicles]]'' (1977) as Mark\n* ''Kill the Golden Goose'' (1979) as Mahuna\n* ''[[The Fish That Saved Pittsburgh]]'' (1979) as Winston Running Hawk\n* ''[[Magnum P.I.]]'' (1982) as native killed by curse\n* ''[[Killpoint]]'' (1984) as Informant in Locker Room (uncredited)\n* ''[[Star Trek III: The Search for Spock]]'' (1984) as Klingon Gunner #2\n* ''[[Cannonball Run II]]'' (1984) as Biker (uncredited)\n* ''[[Hawaiian Heat]]'' (1984) as Harker (main role)\n* ''[[Commando (1985 film)|Commando]]'' (1985) as Vega\n* ''[[Never Too Young to Die]]'' (1986) as Minkie's Partner \n* ''